Recently since 2024, the trend of looksmaxxing has blown up on Tiktok and Instagram. And, it is perhaps the stupdiest shit I've ever heard in my life. The entire concept is this: try to become the most attractive person possible. Now, the inherent qualities of the trend - taking care of your body and feeling good about yourself - those aren't nessecarily bad, but it's the way it's framed that perverts these seemingly healthy ideas. Underlying the entire premise, the main concept is that the *most* important thing is how attractive you are. Not only that, but there is a very specific way your "supposed" to look (i.e. a scale for the bone strucutre or hunter eyes). I'm gonna blow my brains out if I hear this one more time.

When a person ties their self worth to their apperance they will suffer. Because we all at some point will get sick. We all will grow old. We all will *all* at some point lose what we regard to be our identitiy in our looks. Looksmaxxing started in the manosphere and incel forums, usch as Lookism.net, Incels.me, and 4chan. We should all keep in mind that these are some of the most depraved people in the world. Looksmaxxing doesn't just tie one's self worth to their looks, but also judges others stricity on their looks. It relegates people to a one dimensional frame of humanity, flattening out all of the interesting parts of a person. Looks are a factor, but it's such a miniscule thing in the grand scheme of life.

Attraction, at the end of the day, comes from the mind. The "perfect" apperance is just in our heads. Our standards stem from our belief. Without a doubt, life would be more interesting if looks became less important.
